icted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDie Arbeit klärt auf breiter empirischer Basis die variable Zeitreferenz und modale Lesart (irreal/potential) nicht-vergangenheitsbezogener (d.h. temporal umfunktionierter) Formen wie wäre gekommen (Bsp.: Morgen wäre sie gekommen) sowie Bedeutungsunterschiede gegenüber Formen wie käme/würde kommen . Zur Abrundung wird die temporale Umfunktionierung des Konjunktivs II ins 16. Jahrhundert zurückverfolgt.  aThe study uses a broad empirical database to clarify the variable time reference and modal reading ("unreal"/"potential") of non-past related (i.e. temporally refunctioned) forms such as 'wäre gekommen' [would have come] (e.g. 'Morgen wäre sie gekommen' [She would have come tomorrow]) and differences in meaning compared with forms such as 'käme/würde kommen' [would come]. The study concludes with a survey of the temporal refunctioning of the past subjunctive back into the 16th century.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aGerman languagexMood. 0aGerman languagexSubjunctive. 4aKonjunktiv. 4aPragmatik. 4aSemantik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Grammar & Punctuation.2bisacsh  aPast Subjunctive, Semantics, Pragmatics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Linguistics and Semiotics 2000 - 2014z9783110636970oZDB-23-DLS08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2008z9783110212129oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET LINGUISTIK UND LITERATURWISSENSCHAFT  2008z9783110209457oZDB-23-DGA0 cprintz978348430519940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978348497033540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783484970335423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783484970335/original  aEBA_BACKALL